.TH JD-PATH 1 2024-09-02 "jd @tag@"
.
.SH NAME
.
jd-path \- display the path to a directory of the johnny.decimal system
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.
.SY jd-path
.RB { " \- h " | " \-\-help " }
.YS
.
.SY jd-path
.I <jd_path_descriptor>
.YS
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.
.P
The \fBjd-path\fP command can be used to display the path of a directory in the
johnny.decimal system. It can, for example, be used in a shell function to set
up "cd"-like functionality.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Display a short help message.
.
.TP
.I <jd_path_descriptor>
Display the path to a directory with a specific johnny.decimal path descriptor.
This descriptor can either describe an area, category or id of the system. To
display the path to an area, specify the common first digit of its categories.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.
The \fBjd\fP utility exits > 0 if an error occurs, 0 otherwise.
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.
.TP
.I JD_PATH
This environment variable can be used to override the configured file system
path to the johnny.decimal system. Simply set it to the desired path.
.
.TP
.I XDG_CONFIG_HOME
Path to the user-specific configuration directory. Defaults to
\fI\(ti/.config\fP. See \fIFILES\fP.
.
.SH FILES
.
.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/jd/jd.conf
This is the main \fBjd\fP configuration file. See \fBjd.conf\fP(5).
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.
.P
Show the help message:
.IP
.EX
jd path --help
.EE
.
.P
Display the path to the area "10-19 Life admin":
.IP
.EX
$ \fBjd path 1\fP
/home/alex/jd/10-19 Life admin
.EE
.
.P
Display the path to the category "15 House":
.IP
.EX
$ \fBjd path 15\fP
/home/alex/jd/10-19 Life admin/15 House
.EE
.
.P
Display the path to the id "15.02 Travel insurance":
.IP
.EX
$ \fBjd path 15.02\fP
/home/alex/jd/10-19 Life admin/15 House/15.02 Travel insurance
.EE
.
.P
If you want to be able to "cd" to any johnny.decimal directory quickly, you
could, for example, define a shell function "jcd" like this:
.IP
.EX
jcd () {

    jd_path=$(jd path "$@") 
    jd_path_retval=$? 

    if [ $jd_path_retval -eq 0 ] && [ -d $jd_path ]
    then
        cd $jd_path
        return $?

    elif [ ! -z $jd_path ]
    then
        echo $jd_path
        return $jd_path_retval

    else
        return $jd_path_retval
    fi
}
.EE
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.
.nh
